In Chomsky normal form every internal rule has exactly two non-terminals on its right-hand side, and the leaves are produced by single terminal rules of the form A → 'token'.

The start symbol is
    S → NT20 NT46

Hence the sentence produced by S is the concatenation of the yield of NT20 followed by the yield of NT46.  
NT46 has no binary rules – its only productions are

    NT46 → 't9' | 't16' | 't15' | 't0'

so NT46 can generate exactly one token, and that token must be one of  
t9, t16, t15, or t0.

Therefore, in any string generated by the grammar the very last token must be one of those four possibilities.

The string we are asked to check ends with the token t13:

    ... t15 t13   ← last token is t13

Since t13 cannot be produced by NT46, the given string cannot be the yield of S.

Hence the grammar does not generate the string.

No
